https://leetcode.com/problems/rotting-oranges/description/


QUESTION:
Input: grid = [[2,1,1],[1,1,0],[0,1,1]]
Output: 4

SOLUTION:
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CODE COMPLEXITY:O(m*n)
TIME COMPLEXITY:O(m*n)

This solution is better as a bfs solution cause they need the min time in which it gets rotten.
So
-> get all the values where the orange is rotten into a queue 
-> if they are not rotten then have a seperate count
-> now bfs go through horizontal and vertically to check if there is a non rotten orange. contaminate it and increase time and decrease fresh count.
-> if fresh is not 0 then return -1 else the time.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CODE:
class Solution {
    public int orangesRotting(int[][] grid) {
        Queue<int[]>q=new LinkedList<>();
        int fresh=0;
        for(int i=0;i<grid.length;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<grid[0].length;j++){
                if(grid[i][j]==2)q.add(new int[]{i,j});
                if(grid[i][j]==1)fresh++;

            }
        }
        int time=0;
        int dirs[][]={{1,0},{-1,0},{0,1},{0,-1}};
        while(!q.isEmpty()){
            int size=q.size();
            for(int i=0;i<size;i++){
                int cur[]=q.poll();
                for(int dir[]:dirs){
                    int r=dir[0]+cur[0];
                    int c=dir[1]+cur[1];
                    if(r>=0 && r<grid.length && c>=0 && c<grid[0].length && grid[r][c]==1){
                        grid[r][c]=2;
                        fresh--;
                        q.add(new int[]{r,c});
                    }
                }
            }
            time++;
        }
        if(fresh>0)return -1;
        return time>0?time-1:0;
    }
}
